and dare I say it,
our duty to enjoy.

85
00:05:57,375 --> 00:06:01,166
I see. Whoa, that's good!

86
00:06:01,250 --> 00:06:03,458
Of course it is,
this is real cooking.

87
00:06:03,541 --> 00:06:06,750
Hey, those snacks are only
for people who are drinking!

88
00:06:06,833 --> 00:06:07,958
No fair.

89
00:06:08,041 --> 00:06:10,541
You're more than welcome
to try some, though.

90
00:06:10,958 --> 00:06:12,166
If you get me drunk,

91
00:06:12,250 --> 00:06:14,583
I may start talkin'
'bout all sorts of things.

92
00:06:23,875 --> 00:06:27,000
Okay, see, the thing is
by the time I came along

93
00:06:27,083 --> 00:06:28,833
and joined the unit,
Ko had already been

94
00:06:28,916 --> 00:06:30,708
stripped of his Inspector title.

95
00:06:30,791 --> 00:06:33,041
So I don't really
know all the details

96
00:06:33,125 --> 00:06:36,708
but what I heard is that it had
something to do with an Enforcer

97
00:06:36,791 --> 00:06:39,958
who was under his command
at the time getting killed.

98
00:06:40,041 --> 00:06:41,166
How was he killed?

99
00:06:41,250 --> 00:06:42,958
Well, he was chasing
down a suspect,

100
00:06:43,041 --> 00:06:45,750
but the tables turned
and he became a victim.

101
00:06:45,833 --> 00:06:50,125
If I'm remembering right,
his name was Sasayama.

102
00:06:50,208 --> 00:06:52,666
He was killed same way
as the other victims.

103
00:06:52,750 --> 00:06:55,916
From what I hear,
it was all pretty gruesome.

104
00:06:57,166 --> 00:06:58,875
The whole thing
really messed Ko up bad

105
00:06:58,958 --> 00:07:01,708
and caused his Crime
Coefficient to shoot up.

106
00:07:01,791 --> 00:07:03,416
The case may never
have been solved,

107
00:07:03,500 --> 00:07:05,250
but Ko refuses to give up on it.

108
00:07:05,333 --> 00:07:07,833
The stubborn guy is still
investigating it to this day.

109
00:07:07,916 --> 00:07:10,791
That sounds awful.

110
00:07:11,125 --> 00:07:12,333
Now tell me.

111
00:07:12,416 --> 00:07:17,125
How is it you're okay
after drinking so much?

112
00:07:20,916 --> 00:07:23,416
Well, maybe you just
get drunk way too easily.

113
00:07:23,500 --> 00:07:25,083
Enforcer Sasayama?

114
00:07:25,166 --> 00:07:26,916
Oh. There's no
way I could forget

115
00:07:27,000 --> 00:07:29,208
the Specimen Case,
even if I tried.

116
00:07:29,291 --> 00:07:30,750
"Specimen Case?"

117
00:07:30,833 --> 00:07:34,041
Yeah, that was how we all
referred to the investigation.

118
00:07:34,125 --> 00:07:37,375
Akane, you've
heard of plastination?

119
00:07:37,458 --> 00:07:38,500
It's a process they use

120
00:07:38,583 --> 00:07:40,625
to create biological
specimens, right?

121
00:07:40,708 --> 00:07:43,291
Yeah. It's a technique
for preserving tissue.

122
00:07:43,375 --> 00:07:45,833
Water and fat are
replaced by polymers.

123
00:07:45,916 --> 00:07:49,625
But in the Specimen Case,
it was used to commit murder.

124
00:07:51,416 --> 00:07:54,416
First the killer dismembered
and cleaved open the body,

125
00:07:54,500 --> 00:07:57,625
then used plastination to
turn it into a human specimen.

126
00:07:57,708 --> 00:07:59,916
They brought their handiwork
right into the middle of town,

127
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:01,708
and displayed it under

128
00:08:01,791 --> 00:08:05,041
a Holographic illumination in
the entertainment district.

129
00:08:05,125 --> 00:08:06,333
So wrong.

130
00:08:06,416 --> 00:08:08,041
Thousands of
passersby thought they

131
00:08:08,125 --> 00:08:11,000
were just looking
at ordinary environment Holo.

132
00:08:11,083 --> 00:08:13,250
But the truth was, they
were walking right past

133
00:08:13,333 --> 00:08:15,708
the mutilated cadaver
hiding underneath it.

134
00:08:15,791 --> 00:08:17,083
When people found that out,

135
00:08:17,166 --> 00:08:19,875
the Area Stress
jumped up four levels.

136
00:08:19,958 --> 00:08:22,875
It was so bad, they
imposed a news blackout.

137
00:08:22,958 --> 00:08:26,625
Sorry. We shouldn't discuss
this while you're eating.

138
00:08:28,291 --> 00:08:29,916
Why not?

139
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:32,375
It takes a lot to
ruin Yayoi's appetite.

140
00:08:32,458 --> 00:08:34,708
Believe me, that girl
is into some stuff

141
00:08:34,791 --> 00:08:36,791
way more sick and
twisted than this.

142
00:08:36,875 --> 00:08:39,250
Uh, that's...

143
00:08:39,333 --> 00:08:43,083
You were talking about the
Specimen Case, right? Continue.

144
00:08:43,166 --> 00:08:45,000
Well, you see.

145
00:08:45,083 --> 00:08:48,708
Since the procedures were
obviously performed by an expert

146
00:08:48,791 --> 00:08:52,000
the investigation was focused
almost entirely on specialists

147
00:08:52,083 --> 00:08:54,958
in the fields of
pharmacy and chemistry.

148
00:08:55,041 --> 00:08:58,750
But then, in the midst
of all this, Sasayama was.

149
00:08:59,750 --> 00:09:01,500
While looking into a
totally unrelated report

150
00:09:01,583 --> 00:09:03,541
of a missing high school
teacher, they were searching

151
00:09:03,625 --> 00:09:07,416
the guy's apartment and they
came across plastination resin.

152
00:09:07,500 --> 00:09:11,750
It was this guy. Kozaburo Toma.

153
00:09:11,833 --> 00:09:15,541
As soon as he went missing, the
killings came to an abrupt stop.

154
00:09:15,625 --> 00:09:17,750
So it seemed clear he
must've been the culprit.

155
00:09:17,833 --> 00:09:21,458
But all we had was
circumstantial evidence

156
00:09:21,541 --> 00:09:23,875
so it ended up an unsolved case.

157
00:09:23,958 --> 00:09:26,291
On top of that,
Toma didn't have any kind

158
00:09:26,375 --> 00:09:29,000
of background in chemistry,
so even the question of

159
00:09:29,083 --> 00:09:32,750
who created the resin he
used remains a mystery.

160
00:09:32,833 --> 00:09:35,416
You're saying he
had an accomplice?

161
00:09:35,500 --> 00:09:37,500
I don't think we can call
this person an accomplice

162
00:09:37,583 --> 00:09:39,500
since we just have no
way of knowing whether

163
00:09:39,583 --> 00:09:41,541
he had the slightest clue

164
00:09:41,625 --> 00:09:43,416
of what the resin he was
making would be used for.

165
00:09:43,500 --> 00:09:45,875
Hell, we don't even
know how it was acquired

166
00:09:45,958 --> 00:09:50,583
at this point. Only God
knows for sure. I'd say.

167
00:09:57,166 --> 00:09:59,375
I take it you're having
a rough day, as usual.

168
00:09:59,458 --> 00:10:01,791
You can tell?

169
00:10:01,875 --> 00:10:04,958
Considering how crappy you look,
it'd be pretty hard not to.

170
00:10:05,041 --> 00:10:08,208
Guess being on the
fast track gets bumpy.

171
00:10:08,291 --> 00:10:10,000
Keeping all those secrets.

172
00:10:10,083 --> 00:10:13,625
Yeah exactly. It sucks.

173
00:10:15,041 --> 00:10:16,250
So, does this have
something to do

174
00:10:16,333 --> 00:10:18,750
with that loose
cannon you work with?

175
00:10:18,833 --> 00:10:21,458
I feel like I just can't
get a read on him, you know?

176
00:10:21,541 --> 00:10:23,458
And then, to make things
even more confusing,

177
00:10:23,541 --> 00:10:25,791
I just found out
he used to have my job.

178
00:10:25,875 --> 00:10:27,000
Wait, don't tell me
this dude used to

179
